\subsection{Variables}
Some variables need to be redefined, centered and categorized. Here is a description.

\begin{description}

\item[mDeaths] The number of infant deaths a mother experiences. This is the basic \emph{response} variable in all models. In some cases it is categorized.

\item[gmDeaths] The number of infant deaths a grandmother (mother's mother) experiences. It is the primary \emph{explanatory variable}. It is categorized in the categories "0", "1", and "2+".

\item[gmBirths] The number of grandmother's births. Is always (by design) two or larger. In the analyses it is categorized: "2", "3", "4-6", "7+".

\item[mBirthdate] Mother's birthdate expressed as years between 1 January 1 and her day of birth, minus one, \emph{minus 1840}(!). An example: A woman born 3 April 1842 gets the value 1842.253 to begin with. Then subtract 1840, and the value is 2.253. The reason for this \emph{centering} around 1840 is \emph{good statistical practice}: The reference point (zero) of a covariate should lie within the range of the variable in regression analyses.

\item[mAge] Mother's age at the birth of a child. Categorized into the intervals "17-19", "20-22", \ldots, "41-43", "44-49".

\item[parity] The birth order of a mother's child.

\item[childBirthdate] The birthdate of a mother's child, centered in the same way as {\tt mBirthdate}.

\item[gmIMR] Grandmother's infant mortality rate, that is, the number of deaths divided by the number of births. Used as an alternative to {\tt gmDeaths} in some analyses. It is also multiplied by 100 and thus measured on a scale ranging from 0 to 100.

\item[sex] The sex of a mother's child.

\end{description}


